Find the number of functions $f  : \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$ such that
\[f(xy) + f(xz) - f(x) f(yz) \ge 1\]for all real numbers $x,$ $y,$ and $z.$

Setting $y = z = 0,$ we get \[f(0) + f(0) - f(x) f(0) \ge 1,\]so $f(x) \le 1$ for all $x.$ Setting $y = z = 1,$ we get \[f(x) + f(x) - f(x) f(1) \ge 1,\]so $f(x) \ge 1$ for all $x.$ This tells us that the only possible function is $f(x) = 1.$  We readily see that this function works, so there is only $\boxed{1}$ possible function $f(x).$
